In this project, the Partnerships Along the Headwaters of the Americas for Young Scientists (Pathways) Program was developed to train graduate students from across the United States to study complex water management problems in Latin America. A special focus was research related to climate change effects in areas where storage in the winter seasons occurred in the form of glaciers, snowpack, and groundwater in watersheds at high elevations, called headwaters. Because water supplies from these types of headwaters are now shifting because of global warming, downstream communities, industries and ecosystems, collectively called headwater-dependent systems, need to adapt to ensure their viability into the future.


The Pathways program provided 26 US graduate students with research guidance and mentorship including that from established scientists working across Latin America, towards an international research experience. Research was connected to an existing NSF funded research coordination network project, named the Transect of the Americas, which has produced an interdisciplinary team of collaborators from six countries and twelve organizations stretching from Canada to Chile.


Pathways provided the students a program that addressed interdisciplinary, international and interorganizational water resources challenges as they designed their own research studies within diverse headwater-dependent communities in Chile, Costa Rica, Ecuador, and Peru. Over the course of one year, students were involved with six phases: (1) Preparation and planning; (2) A two week summer-school; (3) An international research experience ranging from one to four months; (4) Continued engagement upon return to the US; (5) Culminating virtual or in person events to learn from their experiences; and (6) Continued engagement in Transect of the Americas activities. The first cohort of students experienced delays due to the Covid-19 pandemic.





Project outcomes include:


(1) The Pathways Program developed a two-week summer school curriculum for a case study based interdisciplinary water resources course in an international setting. With minor modifications, this curriculum can be adopted for other international settings and focus areas.


(2) The project gained in-depth understanding of interdisciplinary, international and interinstitutional context for student doing research in headwater-dependent systems;


(3) Twentysix US students received interdisciplinary training in analysis of headwater dependent systems across the Americas;


(4) Pathways students received cultural experiences by spending time in Latin America, interacting with local students and professors as well as with individuals who collaborated on the research;


(5) Students contributed to the science of headwater systems (e.g., drying lakes, glaciers, snowpack dynamics) as well as of headwater-dependent systems (e.g., water supply, hydropower, ecosystem services, dairy industry);


(6) Researchers disseminated scientific findings through peer-reviewed publications with their mentors, peer-reviewed publications with students within their cohorts, dissertation or thesis chapters, conference presentations, and AcrGIS StoryMaps;


(7) Students in the Pathways program gained professional skills in intercultural communication and teamwork in international settings;


(8) Students gained competency in project management and in ways to relate their research to decision-making and policy through stakeholder engagement.





